Project 5: Data Visualization¶

Dataset: Flights¶

by Andy Soelistio¶

Submission Date: January 21, 2019¶

Introduction¶

  • I downloaded three years of flight data -- 2006, 2007, and 2008.. I put them in raw_data/2006, raw_data/2007, and raw_data/2008 folder.

  • I also downloaded airports.csv and carriers.csv. I put them in raw_data/supplement folder.

  • I had done an extensive wrangling on the downloaded data prior to this. I did the wrangling inside wrangling folder. I separate the wrangling according to years. Please refer to wrangle_y_2006, wrangle_y_2007, wrangle_y_2008 inside wrangling folder.
  • Since the target columns of this project are Departure Delay (DepDelayM) and Arrival Delay (ArrDelayM), I will briefly introduce these columns here.
  • Departure Delay Manual (DepDelayM) is measured in minutes.

  • Notice that some are negative numbers and some are positive numbers. Positive numbers mean that actual flight took place after scheduled flight. Negative numbers mean that actual flight took place before scheduled flight. Logically positive delays is what we care about. Therefore, I will create one positive departure delay dataframe. I call it pos_dep_delaym_df. Most data come from this dataframe unless otherwise stated.
  • Another dataframe is called combined_df. This dataframe contains both positive and negative DepDelayM.
  • Arrival Delay Manual (DepDelayM) is measured in minutes.

Reflection on outliers¶

  • Outliers are important data.
  • I dropped outliers or fill them all with zeros or mean values as I had done in project 2 -- Investigate Dataset. What Project 4 -- We Rate Dogs -- taught me is that although useful data consists of small proportion of total data, I don't drop them all. For example in my project 4 Section D, I don't drop dog type column although only 16.3% of its data is non-null.
  • Therefore throughout this project (and my future project), I will not unneccessarily drop columns or rows unless it is really necessary.
  • Therefore I will not delete rows even though DepDelayM is 38 stds away from the mean.

From the calculations and table above, we observe the following:¶

  • The bulk of negative Departure Delay (DepDelayM) happened within 60 minutes. There is only one case when the flight is early to within [-1,200, -1,140] minutes.
  • Negative Departure Delay consists of around 48% of our data.
  • Positive Departure Delay consists of around 40% of our data.
  • Almost 4% of our data falls above the second stds. As a proportion this may not seem like a big number but it translates to around 8,000s rows of our data.

Top Three Carriers¶

  • Southwest Airlines Co. is the top airline in terms of total number flights it made in the dataframe. 16.1% of total flights are made by Southwest Airlines Co. The top three carriers are: Southwest Airlines, American Airlines, and Skywest Airlines.
  • The next logical questions would be: what is the performance of these top-three carriers in terms of departure and arrival delays. I explore this question in this plot and this plot. Top-three carriers are represented as blue-edged barh in those plots.

Bottom Three Carriers¶

  • ATA Airlines, Aloha Airlines, and Hawaiian Airlines are the bottom three carriers. I explore their performance in terms of departure and arrival delays in this plot and this plot. Bottom-three carriers are represented in red-edged barh in those plots.
  • After further wrangling, I manage to create a column called CarriersCount. I will plot Airport against CarriersCount. The objective is to show how many Carriers an Airport has.

scl = [ [0,"rgb(5, 10, 172)"],[0.35,"rgb(40, 60, 190)"],[0.5,"rgb(70, 100, 245)"],\
    [0.6,"rgb(90, 120, 245)"],[0.7,"rgb(106, 137, 247)"],[1,"rgb(220, 220, 220)"] ]

        type = 'scattergeo',

            )
        ))
       ]

layout = dict(

        geo = dict(

I also added an extra information to the plot -- Carrier Distribution information

  • Bars with the blue edge are the top three Carriers in terms of number of flights in the data. The top three Carriers having the largest number of flights are: Skywest Airlines, American Airlines and Southwest Airlines in ascending order. These airlines perform really well considering the large number of flights they operate and having relativley low z-score Delay.
  • Bars with the red edge are the bottom three Carriers in terms of number of flights in the data. The bottom three Carriers are: Hawaiian Airlines, Aloha Airlines and ATA Airlines in ascending order. Aloha Airlines and Hawaiian Airlines have the lowest mean of Departure Delays. This is expected since they have one of the lowest number of flights in the data -- only about 0.4% and 0.8%, respectively. ATA Airlines performance is dismal. It has the second highest mean Departure Delay although it makes up of only 0.1% of total flight!

I also added an extra information to the plot -- Carrier Distribution information

  • Bars with the blue edge are the top three Carriers in terms of number of flights in the data. The top three Carriers having the largest number of flights are: Skywest Airlines, American Airlines and Southwest Airlines in ascending order. These airlines perform really well considering the large number of flights they operate and having relativley low z-score Delay.
  • Bars with the red edge are the bottom three Carriers in terms of number of flights in the data. The bottom three Carriers are: Hawaiian Airlines, Aloha Airlines and ATA Airlines in ascending order. Aloha Airlines and Hawaiian Airlines have the lowest mean of Arrival Delays. This is expected since they have one of the lowest number of flights in the data -- only about 0.4% and 0.8%, respectively. ATA Airlines performance is dismal. It has the third highest mean Arrival Delay although it makes up of only 0.1% of total flight!

Multivariate Exploration¶

Converted Ordinal Variable¶

  • Because we use these ordinal variables extensively in multivariate exploration, I reproduce here for reference.

DepTimeCategory and ArrTimeCategory:
-- 24:00 (not 00:00) -- 02:59: Late Night
-- 03:00 -- 05:59: Early Morning
-- 06:00 -- 08:59: Morning
-- 09:00 -- 11:59: Late Morning
-- 12:00 -- 14:59: Afternoon
-- 15:00 -- 17:59: Late Afternoon
-- 18:00 -- 20:59: Evening
-- 21:00 -- 23:59: Night

airport_size category:
-- v_small_sized airport: 1 Carrier (below 25th percentile)
-- small_sized airport: 2-3 Carriers (above 25th and below 50th percentile)
-- mid_sized airport: 4 - 9 Carriers (above 50th and below 75th percentile)
-- big_sized airport: 10-18 Carriers (above 75th percentile)

Observations on two boxplots above based on pos_depdelaym_df dataframe:¶

  • The first plot on the y-axis is DepDelay in minutes and the y-axis on the second plot is z-score of DepDelayM.
  • Boxplots measure the percentile of Departure Delay (DepDelayM). The horizontal line across each boxplot above represents its median (50th percentile) DepDelayM.
  • The main point to observe from data obtained from pos-depdelaym_df is that the variability of DepDelay is even more pronounced in Late Night across all Airport-sized category.
  • DepDelayM median is the largest at late night across all Airport-sized category.
  • Also note that in general, median delays are cascaded throughout the day starting at Early Morning and ending at LateNight. I call this cascading delays.

Observations on two plots above based on pos_arrdelaym dataframe:¶

  • The first plot on the x-axis is ArrDelay in minutes and the x-axis on the second plot is z-score of ArrDelayM.
  • By eyeballing, longest Arrival Delays happen mostly in 2007 and 2008.

Drill Down¶

  • From previous plots, we see a pattern. MEAN delays are lowest in the morning and highest late into the night. It seems as though delays are cascaded throughout the day.
  • This section attempts to investigate if delays in a particular time category is carried over (cascaded) into the next time category. To do this, I have to track an individual flight number / tail number from early morning into night time.
  • Because the queries do not fit nicely in this presentation, please refer to Section 5.5 of the jupyter notebook.

Causes of Delays¶

  • So we now know that there are no cascading delays. Now we need to know the causes of delays and in what time category do most delays occur in.
  • I have established that there are correlations between CarrierDelay, WeatherDelay, NASDelay, SecurityDelay, LateAircraftDelay and target columns DepDelayM, ArrDelayM. Now I will explore further.

  • Three plots stand out: 1. LateAircraftDelay, 2. CarrierDelay, and 3. Weather Delay.
  • They stand out because longest delays happen at LateNight and EarlyMorning. Their mean delays in LateNight and EarlyMorning category are above mean average.
  • Taken together, data from these three categories make up around 62% of total delayed data (29.06 + 28.52 + 4.38).
  • Therefore, the trend we observe previously (Section 5.2, Section 5.3, and Section 5.4) is not due to cascading delays. It is due to delays caused by LateAircraftDelay, CarrierDelay and WeatherDelay that happened longer at LateNight and EarlyMorning. Also Read Section 5.5, if you need convincing that delays are not cascaded through the day.
